solutions.content:
This problem is not too hard even when you consider operating in place (and it would be rather trivial otherwise: just creating a new array of the same size and populating it with of 2 pointers to write there in alternate order).

In order to solve it, we will use 3 variables:
* `i` and `j` will be our pointers, respectively set to `0` and `1` initially, with the goal to find odd (the former) or even value (the latter);
* `lmt` is going to be the limit of our search, set to be the length of our input.

We will then ran an infinite loop and inside it:
* move `i` to find the first odd value in even positions (if any such is left);
* move `j` to find the first even value in odd positions (if any such is left);
* check if we reached the end of the input and:
	* if not, we swap the values pointed by `i` and `j`;
	* otherwise, it means we are done parsing and just `break` out of the loop.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> sortArrayByParityII(vector<int>& ns) {
        // support variables
        int i = 0, j = 1, lmt = ns.size();
        // parsing ns
        while (true) {
            // moving i in even positions with odd values
            while (i < lmt && !(ns[i] & 1)) i += 2;
            // moving j in odd positions with even values
            while (j < lmt && (ns[j] & 1)) j += 2;
            // swapping if needed
            if (i < lmt && j < lmt) swap(ns[i], ns[j]);
            else break;
        }
        return ns;
    }
};
```

