See also my copying solution here: https://leetcode.com/problems/sort-array-by-parity-ii/discuss/520235/C%2B%2B-Copy-out-to-odd-or-even-addresses-68ms100
# Algorithm

This is a very simple modify in-place approach.
The overall flow is to step 2 index counters through the input array. One indexes odd locations and the other indexes even locations, so their paths interleave and never touch the same location.
* Advance even indexes by 2 until an odd value is hit
* Advance odd indexes by 2 until an even value is hit
* Swap the elements at these indexes to restore the desired state of even values at even indexes and odd values at odd indexes.

# Code
```
        static vector<int> sortArrayByParityII(vector<int> A)
        {
            const unsigned len = A.size();
            unsigned odd = 1u;
            unsigned even = 0u;
            while(even < len)
            {
                // Skip even numbers at even indexes:
                while(even < len  && (A[even] & 1u) == 0u){
                    even += 2u;
                }
                // Skip odd numbers at odd indexes:
                while((odd < len) && (A[odd]  & 1u)){
                    odd += 2u;
                }
                // Either we hit the end of the input or an odd number at an even address
                // and an even number at an odd address. If the latter, swap them:
                if(even < len){
                    swap(A[even], A[odd]);
                }
                // We always increment so that as little code as possible is inside
                // the branch above even though logically the increment belongs inside
                // it:
                even += 2u;
                odd += 2u;
            }
            return A;
        }
```

