solutions.content:
This solution does require a lit bit of familiarity with bit wise operations, otherwise it might be hard to think of the solution, but the encoded array does give you a hint on how you should be thinking.

We're given that the original array will always contain ```1 ... n``` (in some arbitrary order), with ```n``` being odd.

So, let's take an example of ```1, 2, 3, 4, 5```

If we take xor of all elements from ```1 ... 5 ```, we have the following

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3d8000a0-afc3-414f-8a6f-736306e9ff93_1633899260.3070457.png)

We're given an encoded array formed with xor of two elements at a time for the above array

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e8df04cb-8e37-4f5c-a143-35152b1cce6c_1633899031.1095047.png)

Xor has the property that an element xored with itself will be 0, so using that, we can easily get the first element of the original array.
For this we need to xor (fig 1) with only odd elements of (fig 2), because this way we can cancel out all but first element.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/59ad56f0-a608-4c59-a836-29af0b89a9cf_1633899454.6284459.png)

With the first element, we can now get all elements using that same property of xor, for example to get the 2nd element, we just need to xor first element of the given encoded array with the first element we found and continue that sequence

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/36607ecf-b1c4-4927-923b-d021c55c591d_1633899541.354136.png)

```
vector<int> decode(vector<int>& encoded) {
	size_t n = encoded.size() + 1;
	int xor_one_to_n = 0;
	for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
		xor_one_to_n ^= i;
	}

	int xor_odd = 0;
	for(size_t i = 1; i < encoded.size(); i += 2) {
		xor_odd ^= encoded[i];
	}

	int first_element = xor_odd ^ xor_one_to_n;
	vector<int> original(n);
	original[0] = first_element;
	for(size_t i = 1; i < n; i++) {
		original[i] = encoded[i - 1] ^ original[i - 1]; 
	}
	return original;
}
```

