If you have done https://leetcode.com/problems/decode-xored-array/ , you would immediately get the intuition that one needs to figure out the first element of the answer & then can reuse the logic of decode xored array problem.
Illustration :
encoded = [w,x,y,z] => n=4
Say answer[] = [a,b,c,d,e]
According to question, the elements of answer[] are permutation of 1 to n+1, so 1 to 5.
You know that a^b=w; b^c=x; c^d=y; d^e=z
Also a^b^c^d^e = Xor of first n+1 positive numbers
Now your aim is to get the first element i.e. a. As even operations in XOR cancel out, you need to XOR (a^b^c^d^e) with (b^c^d^e) which can be easily evaluated.
One can even figure out the last element (instead of first element) & proceed in similar manner.


```
class Solution {
    public int[] decode(int[] encoded) {
        int allXor=0;
        int n = encoded.length+1;
        //since the perm is a permutation of first n positive integers, so xor of all elements of perm array would be xor of all first n positive numbers (ordering is irrelevant in xor)
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            allXor^=i;
        }

        int xorAllOddButFirstElement=0;//basically gets XOR of all off elements starting from index 1 i.e index 1,3,5,7 and so on.
        for(int i=1;i<encoded.length;i=i+2){
            xorAllOddButFirstElement^=encoded[i];
        }
        int firstElement = allXor^xorAllOddButFirstElement;
        //since you know the firstElement now, it can be reduced to this problem :
        //https://leetcode.com/problems/decode-xored-array/ 
        int[] answer = new int[n];
        answer[0]=firstElement;
        for(int i=0;i<(encoded.length);i++){ 
            answer[i+1] = encoded[i] ^ answer[i];
        }
        return answer;
    }
}
```

