This problem becomes much easier if you use a pencil and a sheet of paper while putting your math skills to use.
First, XOR operation is commutative: if a XOR b = c then c XOR b = a

The encoded array is generated by:

encoded[i] = perm[i] XOR perm[i+1] which by commutative property becomes:

perm[i+1] = perm[i] XOR encoded[i]

Using this fact we can easily generate all elements of permutation array by XORing its previous element with the element of the encoded array at previous index.

The challenge is to find the first element of the permutation array. And here, we do some simple algebra. 

totalPerm = perm[0] XOR perm[1] XOR perm[2] ... perm[n]

Again by commutative property:

perm[0] = totalPerm XOR perm[1] XOR perm[2] ... perm[n]

Since permutation array contains all numbers from 1 to n, we can easily calculate totalPerm by starting from 0 and XORing it with all numbers from 1 to n, i.e. from 1 to encoded.length + 1.

Once we've calculated totalPerm value, we again recall that:

encoded[i] = perm[i] XOR perm[i+1] (encoded[1] = perm[1] XOR perm[2], encoded[2] = perm[2] XOR perm[3] and so on)

So:

perm[0] = totalPerm XOR perm[1] XOR perm[2] XOR perm[3] XOR perm[4] ... perm[n] =
              = totalPerm XOR encoded[1] XOR encoded[3] ... XOR encoded[i] where i is odd.

Hope this helps! Like I said, things become clearer if you use a sheet of paper and do some algebra.
Java code is below.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] decode(int[] encoded) {
        int[] res = new int[encoded.length+1];
        int perm = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i <= encoded.length+1; i ++)
            perm ^= i;
        for(int i = 1; i < encoded.length; i += 2)
            perm ^= encoded[i];
        res[0] = perm;
        for(int i = 1; i < res.length; i ++) {
            res[i] = res[i-1] ^ encoded[i-1];
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

