**Example**

Let the unencoded sequence be [a, b, c, d, e] 

The encoded sequence is then [a^b, b^c, c^d, d^e]

Since we know that the original sequence is a permutation of 1 .. N, we can get (without loss of generality) a ^ b ^ c ^ d ^ e

To get e I need (a ^ b ^ c ^ d ^ e) ^ (a ^ b ^ c ^ d), which I can get by xoring 1st and 3rd elements of the encoded sequence. 

Once we found the last element we can now re-construct the sequence back to front by xoring with the encoded values. (Just to illustrate => e ^ (d ^ e) = d ...)
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> decode(vector<int>& encoded) {
        int all = 0, n = encoded.size() + 1, last = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) all ^= i;
        for (int i = 0; i < encoded.size(); i+=2) last ^= encoded[i];

        last ^= all; // we found the last
        vector<int> ans(n);
        ans[n-1] = last;
        encoded.push_back(0);
        for (int i = n-2; i >= 0; i--) {
            ans[i] = ans[i+1] ^ encoded[i];
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

