# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Since we are given the array whose each element is the xor of 2 elements from the array that we have to return, thus we need to know one of the element inorder to find the 2nd element.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We are given the encoded array, so consider original array that we have to return is perm = [a, b, c, d, e] and we are given encoded = [a^b, b^c, c^d, d^e], so somehow if we can know about any element from `perm` and we can `xor` that with the element from encoded we can get whole array.
Now what we'll do is we'll xor the element from 1 to n (reason i'll tell later). Now it means `a ^ b ^ c ^ d ^ e = x(let)`, now we have encoded array so take 2 element(pair) from it, let say we take `a ^ b` and `c ^ d`, now if you xor `x` with `a ^ b`, the `a ^ b` in x cancels out, similarly if we xor `c ^ d` with x, the `c ^ d` from x cancels out, what do we end up with?? `e` (that is the last element of the array that we need to return). 
Now we can iterate from last to the start and using the `e` we can get the whole array which is similar to the question https://leetcode.com/problems/decode-xored-array/

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] decode(int[] encoded) {
        int n = encoded.length;
        int[] decoded = new int[n + 1];
        int xorAll = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i <= n + 1; i++){
            xorAll ^= i;
        }

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i += 2){
            xorAll ^= encoded[i];
        }
        int last_element = xorAll;
        decoded[n] = last_element;
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--){
            last_element ^= encoded[i];
            decoded[i] = last_element;
        }
        return decoded;
    }
}
