Lets assume our original permutation is 
a b c d e f g

lets say the encoded array is 
1 2 3 4 5 6

therfore,
1=a^b
2=b^c
3=c^d
4=d^e
5=e^f
6=f^g

if we xor 1 3 5 we get,
1^3^5=a^b^c^d^e^f   (eqn 1)

we know that the permutation is of first n numbers. in this example n=7
so if we xor 1...7 we get  a^b^c...^g.

let x=1^2^3.....^7

xoring eqn 1 with x on both sides,
x^1^3^5=g (because on RHS we will have every element twice except g)

now lets try calculate f. 
6=f^g
XORing g on both sides,
6^g=f. 
both g and 6 are known
similary we can get all elements

general equation
ans[i]=ans[i+1]^encoded[i]. (run i from n-2 to 0)

NOTE n is nothing but size of encoded array +1.

