Since there's no official solution to this question, let me explain in detail one possible approach. I will denote the XOR by ⊕ for brevity.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] decode(int[] encoded) {

        // 1) It is easy (see below) to note that
        //
        //                                                 /
        //                                                |  0,  if n = 3 (mod 4),
        //    t := perm[0] ⊕ perm[1] ⊕ ... ⊕ perm[n-1] = <
        //                                                |  1,  if n = 1 (mod 4).
        //                                                 \
        //

        // 2) On the other hand,
        //
        //   t ⊕ encoded[1] ⊕ encoded[3] ⊕ encoded[5] ⊕ ... ⊕ encoded[n-2]
        //       = perm[0] ⊕ perm[1] ⊕ ... ⊕ perm[n-1]
        //             ⊕ (perm[1] ⊕ perm[2]) ⊕ (perm[3] ⊕ perm[4]) ⊕ ... (perm[n-2] ⊕ perm[n-1])
        //       = perm[0]

        // 3) Then recursively, we calculate perm[i+1] = encoded[i] ⊕ perm[i] for i = 1, 2, ..., n-1.

		// (*) Morally, the recursive formulas give (n-1) equations in n variables perm[i].
		//     To find a unique solution, there's an extra equation coming from part 1)

        int[] perm = new int[encoded.length+1];

        perm[0] = ((encoded.length+1) % 4 == 3) ? 0 : 1;

        for (int i = 1; i < encoded.length; i += 2) {
            perm[0] ^= encoded[i];
        }

        for (int i = 1; i < perm.length; i++) {
            perm[i] = encoded[i-1] ^ perm[i-1];
        }

        return perm;
    }
}
```

(*) Here's a rigorous explanation for part 1) above. Indeed, we are calculating the XOR (which I denote by ⊕) of all numbers from 1 to n **odd**. For instance,

* for n = 1 we have trivially 1,

* for n = 3 we have 01 ⊕ 10 ⊕ 11 = 0,

* and so on...

To pass from the cases of n = 1 and n = 3 to a proof by induction, note that **if n is odd**, then everything depends modulo 4, since

(n+1) ⊕ (n+2) ⊕ (n+3) ⊕ (n+4) = 0.

This is because in fact we have (**for odd n!**)

(n+1) ⊕ (n+3) = (n+2) ⊕ (n+4)

For this e.g. recall the interpretation of binary addition via a+b = (a⊕b) + 2*(a&b). Hence for the last formula,
LHS = (n+4) - 2*((n+1)&(n+3)),
RHS = (n+6) - 2*((n+2)&(n+4)).

Now e.g. consider all cases for the last three digits of n:

```
|------------------------------------------|
| last digits | (n+1)&(n+3) | ((n+2)&(n+4))|
|------------------------------------------|
|     001     |      0      |       1      |
|     011     |      4      |       5      |
|     101     |      0      |       1      |
|     111     |      8      |       9      |
|------------------------------------------|
```

The right column differs by one, so it all works out.


For **even n**, this is different! But it also depends mod 4:

* if n = 0 (mod 4), then 1 ⊕ 2 ⊕ ... ⊕ n = n,
* if n = 2 (mod 4), then 1 ⊕ 2 ⊕ ... ⊕ n = n+1.

Why so? Well, simply because we just figured out what's going on with 1 ⊕ 2 ⊕ ... ⊕ n-1: it's either zero or one, in the respective cases.

